        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>SENSITIVITY:

Our target sensitivity of 0.1 mJy for an aggregate bandwidth is driven by our two continuum science goals. For a fiducial dust SED shifted to z=0.87, an infrared luminosity of L(IR) = 5e12 Lsun will translate to an observed 250 GHz flux density of ~1 mJy (Blain et al. 2002). This scaling means that our 4-sigma detection threshold for an individual cluster member will correspond to L(IR) ~ 2.0e12 Lsun, just over the ULIRG threshold, while stacking sets of 10 objects will yield statistical 4-sigma detections of LIRG-level L(IR) ~ 6.3e11 Lsun. Given the 35 objects with spectroscopic redshifts lying within the uniform converage region (Sifon et al. 2013), we expect to be able to determine the dependence of (mean) dust mass on other parameters across at least three bins in each. Considering background galaxies, we know from Lindner et al. (2011) that the 250 GHz number counts of SMGs in blank fields imply we should detect ~28 4-sigma continuum detections of background galaxies in our 2.5'x2.0' area of uniform depth, even before we account for lensing by the cluster.

If we assume a typical line width of 300 km/s, our 4-sigma threshold for line emission from a single source becomes ~0.65 Jy km/s. Translating this flux to line luminosity gives L'(CO(4-3))~1.6e9 K km/s pc^2 and L'(CI)~1.4e9 K km/s pc^2. For a CO(4-3)/CO(1-0) ratio ~0.4 in temperature units, the former corresponds to L'(CO(1-0))~4e9 K km/s pc^2 in the range occupied by LIRGs and ULIRGs in the local universe (Gao &amp; Solomon 2004). Stacking sets of 10 objects will allow us to probe lower flux levels and and mitigate the impact of any unfavorably low CO(4-3)/CO(1-0) of [CI]/CO intensity ratios.

For our spectral setup, ALMA delivers a sensitivity of 0.1 mJy in only 40s of integration; for a 150-pointing mosaic; the total time request is 3.57 hours.

IMAGING:

ALMA's snapshot uv coverage in the C34-1 configuration will yield angular resolution ~1.6" and image fidelity that are sufficient for our goals. Most cluster members will be a few arcseconds in size in optical imaging, so identifications will not be a problem, and we will be able to look for star/ISM offsets caused by the ICM. For background SMGs, our counterpart identification will be limited as much by the resolutions of optical, infrared, and radio data as by the ALMA data per se. We have chosen a 2.5'x2.0' rectangular mosaic that includes the brightest cluster galaxy, 34 other cluster members with spectroscopic redshifts, the strongly lensed arc, and significant lengths of lensing critical curves. We will be able to observe all 35 cluster members in CO(4-3) and 29 of 35 in [CI], with additional prospects for including sources that are outside the uniform coverage area but within one primary beamwidth of its edge.

CORRELATOR SETUP:

Our spectral setup maximizes the number of spectroscopically confirmed cluster members that can be observed in both CO(4-3) and [CI]. We deploy two spectral windows apiece in the lower and upper sidebands, with each pair separated by 1.875 GHz to give total bandwidths of 3.75 GHz centered at 246.6 and 262.6 GHz. These span IF ranges that avoid excess LO1 noise and access redshift ranges 0.8555 &lt; z(CO) &lt; 0.8839 and 0.8609 &lt; z(CI) &lt; 0.8877. Channel widths are well matched to the typical uncertainties of our optical redshifts (Sifon et al. 2013).

CALIBRATION, BANDPASS ACCURACY, SCHEDULING, DATA RATE, OTHER:

This proposal imposes no special requirements.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
